The paper deals with the computational aspects of the Mobius transformation, which is a mathematical tool used in Dempster-Shafer theory of evidence. This theory is widely used in artificial intelligence and machine learning, hence the paper is likely to belong to the cs.AI sub-category. The paper also discusses the fast algorithms for computing the Mobius transformation, which involves optimization and computational complexity, making it relevant to the cs.LG sub-category. The paper also deals with the combination rule of Dempster-Shafer theory, which falls under the cs.DS sub-category. The paper also discusses the commonality function, which is a measure of similarity between sets, making it relevant to the cs.IT sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with handling uncertainty in expert systems, which is a topic in the cs.SI sub-category.
